{{About|the dietary recommendation that became popular in the 1990s|food of the areas around the [[Mediterranean Sea]]|Mediterranean cuisine}}
The '''Mediterranean diet''' is a modern nutritional recommendation inspired by the traditional dietary patterns of southern [[Italy]], [[Greece]], and [[Spain]]<!-- these are the regions which orginally *inspired* it, not the regions where it is found--><ref>Alberto Capatti ''et al.'', ''Italian Cuisine: A Cultural History'', p. 106.;  Silvano Serventi and Francoise Sabban, ''Pasta'', p. 162.</ref><ref>[http://www.drweil.com/drw/u/WBL02211/Eat-Like-a-Greek-to-Avoid-Skin-Cancer.html Eat like a Greek to avoid skin cancer]</ref> The principal aspects of this diet include proportionally high consumption of [[olive oil]], [[legume]]s, [[Whole foods | unrefined cereals]], [[fruit]]s, and [[vegetable]]s, moderate to high consumption of fish, moderate consumption of dairy products (mostly as cheese and yogurt), moderate wine consumption, and low consumption of meat and meat products.<ref>"Get your Meds: the Mediterranean Diet and Health", Ellen Gooch, Epikouria Magazine, Fall 2005</ref>

On November 17, 2010, [[UNESCO]] recognized this diet pattern as an Intangible Cultural Heritage of [[Italy]], [[Greece]], [[Spain]] and [[Morocco]].<ref>Unesco, [http://www.unesco.org/culture/ich/en/RL/00394 The Mediterranean diet]</ref>

Despite its name, this diet is not typical of all [[Mediterranean cuisine]]. In Northern Italy, for instance, [[lard]] and [[butter]] are commonly used in cooking, and olive oil is reserved for dressing salads and cooked vegetables.<ref>Massimo Alberini, Giorgio Mistretta, ''Guida all'Italia gastronomica'', Touring Club Italiano, 1984</ref> In North Africa, wine is traditionally avoided by Muslims. In both [[North Africa]] and the [[Middle Eastern cuisine|Middle East]], sheep's tail fat and rendered butter ([[ghee|''samna'']]) are the traditional staple fats, with some exceptions.<ref>{{cite book |author=Tapper, Richard; Zubaida, Sami |title=A Taste of Thyme: Culinary Cultures of the Middle East |publisher=Tauris Parke Paperbacks |year=2001 |isbn=1-86064-603-4 |page=43}}</ref>

