Another study reported in February 2010 found that the diet may help keep the brain healthy by reducing the frequency of mini-strokes that can contribute to mental decline.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://news.health.com/2010/02/08/mediterranean-diet-may-help-keep-you-smarter/ |title=Mediterranean Diet May Help Keep You Smarter - Health News - Health.com |publisher=News.health.com |date=2010-02-08 |accessdate=2010-08-27}}</ref>
Mediterranean Diet is becoming a comprehensive  popular and successful translational paradigm for the promotion of healthier lifestyles.<ref name="pmid18511765" />

A 2011 [[meta-analysis]] published in the ''Journal of the American College of Cardiology'' analyzed the results of 50 studies (35 clinical trials, 2 prospective and 13 cross-sectional) covering about 535,000 people to examine the effect of a Mediterranean diet on [[metabolic syndrome]]. The researchers reported that a Mediterranean diet is associated with lower blood pressure, blood sugar, and [[triglyceride]]s.<ref>
